Ngôn ngữ chính thức sử dụng cho nội dung của website công cộng của Tòa Thượng Thẩm Los Angeles là Anh Ngữ. Google™ Translate là dịch vụ phiên dịch ngôn ngữ miễn phí trên mạng có thể phiên dịch văn bản và những trang web sang nhiều ngôn ngữ khác nhau. Phiên dịch bằng máy điện toán chỉ có kết quả xấp xỉ gần giống nội dung nguyên thủy của website này. Không nên xem bản dịch là chính xác và trong một số trường hợp bản dịch có thể sử dụng ngôn ngữ sai hoặc xúc phạm.

Tòa Thượng Thẩm Los Angeles không bảo đảm mức chính xác, đáng tin hoặc nhanh chóng của bất cứ tin tức nào do Google™ Translate hoặc bất cứ hệ thống phiên dịch nào khác thực hiện. Ngoài ra, không thể phiên dịch được một số ứng dụng, hồ sơ hoặc loại khác gồm cả biểu đồ, hình ảnh hoặc một số dạng văn kiện lưu động (pdfs).

Xin lưu ý là khi yêu cầu phiên dịch là quý vị rời khỏi website của Tòa Thượng Thẩm Los Angeles. Tòa Thượng Thẩm Los Angeles không ủng hộ việc sử dụng Google™ Translate. Có thể sử dụng các dịch vụ phiên dịch khác để xem website của chúng tôi. Bất cứ người hoặc thực thể nào dựa vào tin tức thu thập từ bất cứ hệ thống phiên dịch nào đều phải tự chịu rủi ro. Khi phiên dịch xong, quý vị tự chịu bất cứ rủi ro nảo về những chỗ không chính xác, sai lầm hoặc những vấn đề khác gặp phải. Tòa Thượng Thẩm Los Angeles không chịu trách nhiệm về bất cứ thiệt hại hoặc vấn đề nào có thể phát xuất từ việc sử dụng Google™ Translate hoặc bất cứ hệ thống phiên dịch nào khác.

Nếu quý vị có bất cứ thắc mắc nào về Google™ Translate, xin bấm vào đường nối sau đây: Google™ Translate FAQs.

로스앤젤레스 상급법원 공개 웹사이트의 내용에 사용되는 공식 언어는 영어입니다. Google™ Translate(번역)는 텍스트와 웹페이지를 다른 언어로 번역할 수 있는 무료 온라인 언어 번역 서비스입니다. 컴퓨터화된 번역은 단지 웹사이트의 원래 내용과 비슷할 뿐입니다. 이 번역은 정확하다고 생각해서는 안되고, 어떤 경우에는 부정확하거나 모욕적인 언어가 포함될 수도 있습니다.

로스앤젤레스 상급법원은 Google™ Translate 또는 다른 번역 시스템으로 번역된 정보의 정확성, 신뢰성 또는 적시성을 보증하지 않습니다. 또한, 그래프, 사진 또는 이동 가능 문서 형식(pdf)을 포함하는 어떤 애플리케이션, 파일 또는 항목을 번역할 수 없습니다.

번역이 요청되면, 로스앤젤레스 상급법원 웹사이트를 떠난다는 것을 확인해 주십시오. 로스앤젤레스상급법원은 Google™ Translate의 사용을 보증하지 않습니다. 저희 웹사이트를 보시려면 다른 번역 서비스를 이용할 수도 있습니다. 번역 시스템에서 얻은 정보에 의존하는 개인이나 단체는 위험을 무릅쓰고 그렇게 합니다. 번역이 완료되면, 부정확성, 오류 또는 다른 문제가 발생할 위험을 감수합니다. 로스앤젤레스 상급법원은 Google™ Translate 또는 다른 번역 시스템을 사용함으로써 발생 가능한 손해 또는 문제에 대해 책임을 지지 않습니다.

Google™ Translate에 대한 질문이 있는 경우, 다음의 링크를 클릭해 주십시오: Google™ Translate FAQs.

번역하십시오

DEPARTMENT 205 LAW AND MOTION RULINGS


Case Number: 22SMCV01934    Hearing Date: May 22, 2024    Dept: 205

Superior Court of California 

County of Los Angeles – West District 

Beverly Hills Courthouse / Department 205 

 

LEO DAVID,   

 

Plaintiff, 

v. 

 

AURICE VELOSO,  

 

Defendant. 

 

  Case No.:  22SMCV01934 C/W  

  22SMCV01934 [Lead Case] 

  

  Hearing Date:  May 22, 2024 

  [TENTATIVE] ORDER RE: 

  XCVI, LLC’S MOTIONS TO COMPEL  

  RESPONSES TO FORM  

  INTERROGATORIES-GENERAL (SET  

  ONE), FORM INTERROGATORIES- 

  EMPLOYMENT (SET ONE), SPECIAL  

  INTERROGATORIES (SET ONE),  

  REQUESTS FOR ADMISSIONS (SET  

  ONE), AND REQUESTS FOR  

  PRODUCTION OF DOCUMENTS (SET  

  ONE) 

AURICE VELOSO,   

 

Cross-Complainant, 

v. 

 

LEO DAVID, et al.,  

 

Defendants. 

 

  

  

  

 

 

BACKGROUND 

This case arises from an employment dispute.  Aurice Veloso was a caregiver for Leo David and his late wife, Ruth David.  David alleges Veloso stole monies and personal property and engaged in financial and physical elder abuse.   

Meanwhile, Veloso has brought her own claims of discrimination, harassment, and retaliation.  Veloso alleges that David asked her to sleep with him in exchange for improved working conditions and other financial incentives including a house, a car and tuition.  Veloso further alleges that despite working around the clock, she was not compensated for overtime or provided rest and meal breaks.  David then terminated Veloso when she opposed his alleged discrimination and harassment.   

David paid Veloso’s wages through various companies he owned, including XCVI, LLC (“XCVI”) and Construction for Less, Inc. (CFL).  Veloso alleges these corporate defendants ratified and adopted the conduct of David. 

This hearing is on XCVI’s five motions to compel responses to requests for admissions, special interrogatories, form interrogatories-general, form interrogatories-employment, and requests for production of documents.  XCVI argues that Veloso failed to respond to the requests and accordingly, has waived all objections.  XCVI also seeks monetary sanctions on the ground Veloso has misused the discovery process by failing to timely respond.  Veloso submitted oppositions to these motions, but they were filed late and without leave to file them late. In addition, XCVI points out that Veloso once again failed to cooperate to submit a joint statement in connection with these motions. Nevertheless, the Court elects to consider Veloso’s oppositions and her “Responses” to the “Joint Statement” filed by XCVI. 

LEGAL STANDARD  

A motion to compel an initial response can be made on the ground that a party did not serve a timely response to interrogatories or a demand to produce. (Code Civ. Proc., §§ 2030.290, subd. (a) [interrogatories], 2031.300, subd. (a) [demand to produce]; see¿Sinaiko Healthcare Consulting, Inc. v. Pacific Healthcare Consultants (2007) 148 Cal.App.4th 390, 404 (Sinaiko).)  

To establish this ground, a movant must show: (1) proper service; (2) expiration of the deadline for the initial response, 30 days after service or on date agreed to by parties, and (3) no timely response.  (See¿Code Civ. Proc., §§ 2030.080, 2030.090, 2030.260, 2031.040, 2031.260, 2031.300.) 

Where the court grants a motion to compel responses, sanctions shall be imposed against a party, person, or attorney who unsuccessfully makes or opposes a motion to compel, unless the person or entity acted with substantial justification or the sanction would otherwise be unjust. (Code Civ. Proc., §§ 2030.290, 2031.90, 2033.280, subds. (c);¿Cal. Rule of Court, rule 3.1348.)  In addition, the court may award sanctions for any misuse of discovery process.  (Code Civ. Proc. §§ 2023.010¿and¿2023.030.)  A failure to timely respond constitutes a misuse of the discovery process.  (Code Civ. Proc, § 2023.010, subd. (d).)¿ 

Where a party fails to timely respond to a request for admission, the propounding party may move for an order that the genuineness of any documents and the truth of any matters specified in the requests be deemed admitted.  (Code Civ. Proc., § 2033.280, subd. (b).)  The party who failed to respond waives any objections to the demand, unless the court grants them relief from the waiver, upon a showing that the party (1) has subsequently served a substantially compliant response, and (2) that the party’s failure to respond was the result of mistake, inadvertence, or excusable neglect.  (Code Civ. Proc., § 2033.280, subds. (a)(1)-(2).) 

The court shall grant a motion to deem admitted requests for admissions, “unless it finds that the party to whom the requests for admission have been directed has served, before the hearing on the motion, a proposed response to the requests for admission that is in substantial compliance with Section 2033.220.”  (Code Civ. Proc., § 2033.280, subd. (c).) 

Where a party fails to provide a timely response to requests for admission, “[i]t is mandatory that the court impose a monetary sanction under Chapter 7 (commencing with Section 2023.010) on the party or attorney, or both, whose failure to serve a timely response to requests for admission necessitated this motion.”  (Code Civ. Proc., § 2033.280, subd. (c).)  While delayed responses may avoid a motion to deem admitted, they will not avoid monetary sanctions.  (Code Civ. Proc. § 2033.280 subd. (c); Gonzales v. Harris, 2021 Cal. Super. LEXIS 29267 at *6 (even if delayed responses are served, sanctions are mandatory because the motion had to be brought, regardless of whether it is ultimately denied because responses are served before the hearing).)  

MEET AND CONFER 

 

On March 27, 2024, XCVI’s counsel sent Veloso a letter addressing Veloso’s failure to respond to XCVI’s discovery requests.  (Ex. 7 to McKeon Decl.)  The letter asked Veloso to produce substantive answers (without objections) and produce any responsive documents by the close of business on April 1, 2024.  Veloso did not provide responses or responsive documents by that date.  (McKeon Decl. ¶9.)   

On March 29, 2024, Veloso’s counsel claimed she was not served with the discovery requests.  XCVI has an affidavit from the person who personally served Veloso’s counsel’s office with the discovery requests.  (Ex. 8 to McKeon Decl.)  Veloso’s counsel then claimed the parties agreed to e-mail service only.  XCVI maintains that counsel agreed to accept service by e-mail but the parties did not agree that documents must be served by e-mail.  In any event, on April 3, 2024, XCVI’s counsel provided Veloso’s counsel with courtesy copies of the discovery requests by e-mail.  (McKeon Decl. ¶14.)  Veloso still did not respond to the discovery requests.  (Motion at 4:16-17.)   

The parties participated in an informal discovery conference on May 1, 2024 and May 3, 2024.  Ahead of the IDC, the parties submitted a joint statement.  (Ex. 6 to McKeon Decl.)  In that statement, Veloso’s counsel stated: “By the time of [the May 1 IDC, Veloso] will have responded to the discovery at issue[.]”  (Id. at 5:23-24.)  However, Veloso still has not responded to the discovery requests.  (Motion at 5:22-23.)  The court considered the discovery issues at the IDC and granted XCVI permission to file its five motions to compel.  (McKeon Decl. ¶14.)   

On these facts, the Court concludes XCVI has sufficiently complied with its meet and confer obligations.   

DISCUSSION 

 

On February 20, 2024, XCVI personally served written discovery requests on Veloso.  (Exs. 1-5 to McKeon Decl.)  Veloso’s responses were due March 21, 2024.  Veloso did not respond within the deadline, and therefore, waived her objections.  (Sinaiko, 148 Cal.App.4th 390, 403 (a party who “fails to serve a timely response to the discovery request waives any objection to the request, including one based on privilege or the protection of the attorney work product”).)     

Veloso argues that the discovery requests were not served by e-mail, in violation of the parties’ e-mail service agreement.  The agreement states that “all service documents to Plaintiff [shall] be served through electronic service at the following email addresses”. (Ex. 1 to Abrolat Decl.) XCVI responds that the agreement only requires counsel to accept service by e-mail; it does not confine the parties to serve documents only by e-mail.  The Court need not resolve this dispute because XCVI served Veloso by e-mail on April 3, 2024, making her deadline to respond May 6, 2024.  (Ex. 11 to McKeon Decl.)  She served no response by that date, either. Veloso never addresses this argument in her Opposition.  

Veloso argues the requests are excessively burdensome and harassing, and they are also duplicative of discovery answered long ago. They purportedly mirror and seek the same information previously served by David to Veloso on March 20, 2023, to which Veloso claims she provided complete and verified responses in October 2023. If that were so, then Veloso should have served objections to the requests on those grounds. Alternatively, if indeed the discovery was truly duplicative and Veloso served code-compliant responses to the prior requests, then Veloso could have served the same responses. Instead, Veloso chose not to respond at all, and her objections are therefore waived. Additionally, given the breadth and scope of Veloso’s allegations, it’s not apparent to the Court that XCVI’s discovery is disproportionate to those allegations. 

Veloso also relies on an IDC Minute Order which states “Plaintiff [David] will also withdraw duplicative interrogatories/requests.” (Ex. 4 to Abrolat Decl.) Veloso argues that pursuant to this order, XCVI was required to withdraw any discovery requests that were duplicative of prior requests served by David. But this order does not save Veloso. It was not directed to XCVI, and in any event, the Court’s order did not revive waived objections.  

Accordingly, the Court grants XCVI’s motions to compel initial responses.  Veloso is ordered to provide responses without objections to the form interrogatories-general, form interrogatories-employment, requests for production of documents and special interrogatories within 10 calendar days of this Order.  Veloso is deemed to have admitted the requests for admissions.   

XCVI also seeks sanctions in the amount of $13,750.  The Court concludes sanctions are mandatory as to Veloso’s failure to timely respond to the requests for admissions.  (Code Civ. Proc., § 2033.280, subd. (c).)  The Court also concludes sanctions are warranted as to the other requests given Veloso’s misuse of the discovery process in failing to timely respond.  (Code Civ. Proc. §§ 2023.010¿and¿2023.030.)   

In determining the appropriate amount of sanctions, the Court starts with the lodestar which is the reasonable hourly rate multiplied by the reasonable hours spent. (PLCM Group v. Drexler (2000) 22 Cal.4th 1084, 1096; see also Ketchum v. Moses (2001) 24 Cal.4th 1122, 1132.)  XCVI’s counsel has been practicing since 2014.  The Court concludes that his hourly rate of $550 is a reasonable rate for attorneys in the prevailing market with 10 years experience.  (Gatdula v. CRST Int'l, Inc. (C.D. Cal. Aug. 26, 2015) 2015 U.S. Dist. LEXIS 193440¿*31 (finding hourly rate of $550 for lawyer with 10 years experience was reasonable in 2015); Elder v. Nat'l Conf. of Bar Examiners (N.D. Cal. Sept. 12, 2011) 2011 U.S. Dist. LEXIS 102205, at *14, n.4¿(finding $535 per hour to be a reasonable rate for an attorney with eight years experience in 2011).)¿ 

As to the reasonable hours spent, XCVI’s counsel attests he has spent 15 hours preparing the five motions to compel, conducting research in support of the motions, preparing the joint statements, preparing his declaration and preparing the proposed order.  He expects to spend another 10 hours preparing the replies and preparing for and attending the hearing.  The Court concludes these hours are excessive.  The five motions are largely identical and should have required little work to conform to each discovery request.  The Court concludes that 12 hours is more reasonable, and awards sanctions in the amount of $6,600 jointly and severally against Veloso and her counsel.   

The Court denies without prejudice XCVI’s request for evidentiary and/or terminating sanctions, noting that there is a motion on calendar on June 6, 2024 seeking similar relief. 

CONCLUSION 

 

For the foregoing reasons, the Court GRANTS XCVI’s motions to compel responses to requests for admissions, special interrogatories, form interrogatories-general, form interrogatories-employment, and requests for production of documents.  Veloso is required to respond to the special interrogatories, form interrogatories-general, form interrogatories-employment and requests for production within 10 calendar days of this Order.  Veloso is deemed to have admitted the requests for admissions.  The Court also awards sanctions in the amount of $6,600 against Veloso and her counsel, jointly and severally.   

 

IT IS SO ORDERED.

Case Number: 22SMCV02593    Hearing Date: May 22, 2024    Dept: 205

 

 

 

Superior Court of California 

County of Los Angeles – West District  

Beverly Hills Courthouse / Department 205 

 

 

OLIVER KABILKA, et al.,  

 

Plaintiffs, 

v. 

 

STARRY, INC., et al.,  

 

Defendants. 

 

  Case No.:  22SMCV02593 

  

  Hearing Date:  May 22, 2024 

  ORDER RE: 

  DEFENDANTS AMERICAN TOWERS,  

  LLC AND GTP STRUCTURES I, LLC’S  

  DEMURRER TO FIRST AMENDED  

  COMPLAINT 

 

 

BACKGROUND 

This case arises from the installation of antennas and transmission equipment in an apartment complex which purportedly caused Plaintiffs Oliver Kabilka and Phillip Kabilka to suffer headaches, dizziness, fatigue and difficulty falling or staying asleep.  (First Amended Complaint (“FAC”) ¶¶15-16.)     

Plaintiffs are tenants in an apartment complex located at 2800 Neilson Way, Santa Monica, California.  (FAC ¶1.)  Plaintiff’s apartment building is part of a twin tower residential complex (2700 and 2800 Neilson Way).  The building at 2700 Neilson Way is commonly referred to as “North Tower” while the building at 2800 is commonly referred to as the “South Tower.”  (FAC ¶1.)     

Defendants GTP and American Tower entered into a Rooftop Lease Agreement with the owner of the twin tower complex, and thereafter both defendants entered into a Rooftop License Agreement with Defendant Starry Inc., giving Starry Inc. a non-exclusive license and right to use certain space designated in the Rooftop Lease Agreement.  (FAC ¶10.)   

American Towers contracted with Starry Inc. to install antennas and transmission equipment on the rooftop of the apartment building.  (FAC ¶11.)  GTP, American Towers and Starry Inc. are alleged to operate, service and/or maintain the equipment.  (FAC ¶13.)  Plaintiffs allege that the equipment emits radio frequency (RF) radiation as well as electro-magnetic field (EMF) radiation.  (FAC ¶14.)    

 Plaintiffs allege American Towers and GPT were negligent in (1) allowing and permitting Starry Inc. to install its equipment on the rooftop of the South Tower when the Rooftop Lease Agreement and Rooftop License Agreement designated and gave rights only to the North Tower, and (2) allowing Starry Inc. to operate its equipment without the required governmental permits and approvals and in violation of the Rooftop Lease Agreement and License Agreement. 

This hearing is on American Towers and GTP’s (Moving Defendants’) demurrer.  Moving Defendants argue that Plaintiffs’ sole claim for negligence fails because Plaintiffs have made no allegations that would support a finding that Moving Defendants owed any duty to Plaintiffs.     

REQUEST FOR JUDICIAL NOTICE  

Moving Defendants request judicial notice of a rooftop lease agreement dated July 12, 2010 between Shores Barrington LLC and Global Tower Assets LLC.  The Court grants the request as the agreement is repeatedly referenced in the Complaint.  Where a plaintiff references a document in his or her complaint, but fails to attach a copy of that document to the complaint, the Court may take judicial notice of the document.¿ (See, e.g.,¿Ingram v. Flippo¿(1999) 74 Cal.App.4th 1280, 1285 n.3¿(judicial notice appropriate where complaint referenced to, and¿excerpted quotes from, documents not attached as exhibits to the¿complaint);¿Ascherman v. Gen. Reinsurance Corp., 183 Cal.App.3d 307, 310-11 (1986)¿(judicial notice taken of reinsurance¿contract and release which was¿referenced in the complaint);¿Marina Tenants Ass'n v. Deauville Marina Dev. Co.¿(1986) 181 Cal.App.3d 122, 130¿(taking judicial notice of master lease that was quoted in complaint and formed the basis of the allegations in the complaint);¿Swiss Park, Inc. v. City of Duarte¿(1982) 136 Cal.App.3d 755, 758¿(court took judicial notice of text and map from redevelopment plan, parts of which were referenced in the complaint);¿Purcell v. Colonial Ins. Co. (1971) 20 Cal.App.3d 807, 810¿(taking judicial notice of agreement referenced in but not attached to the complaint).  

MEET AND CONFER   

Code Civ. Proc. § 430.41 requires that before the filing of a demurrer, the moving party “shall meet and confer in person or by telephone” with the party who filed the pleading that is subject to demurrer for the purpose of determining whether an agreement can be reached that would resolve the objections to be raised in the demurrer. (Code Civ. Proc. § 430.41(a).)  The parties are to meet and confer at least five days before the date the responsive pleading is due. (Code Civ. Proc § 430.41(a)(2).)  Thereafter, the moving party shall file and serve a declaration detailing their meet and confer efforts. (Code Civ. Proc. § 430.41(a)(3).)  Moving Defendants submit the Declaration of Amin Al-Sarraf which shows the parties met and conferred by telephone on April 8, 2024, more than five days before the demurrer was filed.  This satisfies the meet and confer requirements of § 430.41.   

LEGAL STANDARD 

“[A] demurrer tests the legal sufficiency of the allegations in a complaint.” (Lewis v. Safeway, Inc. (2015) 235 Cal.App.4th 385, 388.)  A demurrer can be used only to challenge defects that appear on the face of the pleading under attack or from matters outside the pleading that are judicially noticeable.  (See Donabedian v. Mercury Ins. Co. (2004) 116 Cal.App.4th 968, 994 (in ruling on a demurrer, a court may not consider declarations, matters not subject to judicial notice, or documents not accepted for the truth of their contents).)  For purposes of ruling on a demurrer, all facts pleaded in a complaint are assumed to be true, but the reviewing court does not assume the truth of conclusions of law. (Aubry v. Tri-City Hosp. Dist. (1992) 2 Cal.4th 962, 967.)  

Leave to amend must be allowed where there is a reasonable possibility of successful amendment. (See Goodman v. Kennedy (1976) 18 Cal.3d 335, 349 (court shall not “sustain a demurrer without leave to amend if there is any reasonable possibility that the defect can be cured by amendment”); Kong v. City of Hawaiian Gardens Redevelopment Agency (2002) 108 Cal.App.4th 1028, 1037 (“A demurrer should not be sustained without leave to amend if the complaint, liberally construed, can state a cause of action under any theory or if there is a reasonable possibility the defect can be cured by amendment.”).)  The burden is on the complainant to show the Court that a pleading can be amended successfully. (Blank v. Kirwan (1985) 39 Cal.3d 311, 318.) 

DISCUSSION 

Moving Defendants argue that Plaintiff has failed to allege the existence of a duty.  The Court agrees. 

To establish a cause of action for negligence, a plaintiff must allege facts showing a legal duty to use due care, breach of the duty, causation and damages.  (McIntyre v. Colonies-Pacific LLC (2014) 228 Cal.App.4th 664, 671.)  As to the first element, a plaintiff must allege facts “showing the existence of a duty of care.”  (Roy Supply Inc. v. Wells Fargo Bank (1995) 39 Cal.App.4th 1051, 1076.)  A demurrer is appropriate when a complaint fails to show that a duty existed.  (McGettigan v. Bay Area Rapid Transit Dist. (1997) 57 Cal.App.4th 1011, 1024 (affirming trial court’s sustaining of demurrer without leave to amend when plaintiff failed to show the existence of a duty owed by defendant).) 

Here, Plaintiff has not shown how American Towers owed them a duty.  Plaintiff alleges American Towers had “control of the rooftop area” pursuant to the Rooftop Lease Agreement, and as a result, American Towers owed them a duty.  (FAC ¶¶ 23, 24)  But American Towers was not a party to the Rooftop Lease Agreement.  (Ex. 1 to RJN).  The agreement was between Shores Barrington LLC and GTP.  (Id.)  And therefore, even if the contract could create a duty, no such duty was imposed on American Towers.  

  In any event, the mere act of entering into the Lease does not suffice to show Moving Defendants owed a duty to Plaintiffs.  Plaintiffs do not allege anything in the Lease that would give rise to a duty.  There is no allegation that the Lease, for example, created a special relationship between Moving Defendants and Plaintiffs, creating a duty on the part of Moving Defendants.  ¿Generally, “a¿special relationship arises by¿contract only if the contract itself imposes a¿duty” to protect. (McHenry v. Asylum Entertainment Delaware, LLC¿(2020) 46 Cal.App.5th 469, 485–486 [260 Cal. Rptr. 3d 51].)  Such a¿special relationship requires “a specific promise” in the¿contract to “provide specific protection.” (Bom v. Superior Court¿(2020) 44 Cal.App.5th 1, 16.)¿ Plaintiffs do not argue the Lease contained any specific promise to protect them. 

Plaintiffs argue that the Rooftop Lease Agreement gave Moving Defendants control of the rooftop area, and their control is sufficient to create a duty to protect owed to persons using the property.  But as discussed above, American Towers is not a party to the Rooftop Lease Agreement.  Further, even as to GTP and even under Plaintiffs’ logic, its control of the rooftop area creates a duty only to protect owed to persons using the rooftop.  Plaintiffs were not using the rooftop.  Rather, they allege that Starry Inc.’s use of the rooftop caused them injury. 

Alcaraz v. Vece (1997) 14 Cal.4th 1149, 1162, 1166 does not support Plaintiff’s position.  There, Plaintiff tenant sued defendant landlords for personal injuries suffered when he stepped into a water meter box located in the lawn in front of the rental property. The trial court granted summary judgment for the defendants because the meter box was not located on the defendants’ property, but within an adjacent strip of land owned by the city. The appellate court ruled that the trial court erred in granting summary judgment for defendants. On appeal, the court affirmed the decision of the appellate court, holding that a triable issue of fact existed as to whether the defendants exercised control over the strip of land owned by the city so as to give rise to a duty to protect or warn persons entering the land. The court found that it was undisputed that the defendants did not own the narrow strip of land on which the meter box was located.  However, evidence regarding the defendants’ maintenance of the lawn, and construction of a fence, subsequent to the incident, was highly relevant regarding whether the defendants exercised control over the strip of land owned by the city.  Unlike here, the plaintiff in Alcaraz was injured while on the property (the lawn) over which the defendants were exercising control. 

Likewise, Colonial v. Van & Storage, Inc. v. Superior Court (2022) 76 Cal.App.5th 487, 497 does not support Plaintiff’s position.  There, the trial court denied an employer’s motion for summary judgment on tort claims arising from an incident at the private residence of an employee who worked from home and was using the home for a business meeting when a family member of the employee assaulted a coworker and a business associate.  The Court of Appeal granted writ relief.  The court held that the employer had no duty to protect against third party criminal conduct in the employee’s home because the duty to provide a safe place to work (Lab. Code, § 6400, subd. (a)) did not apply to an offsite meeting place; unforeseeability counseled against imposing a duty of care (Civ. Code, § 1714, subd. (a)) regardless of commercial benefit; there was no special relationship absent evidence the employer could have prevented the harm, and the assault was outside the scope of the employer-employee relationship.  Claims for intentional infliction of emotional distress and vicarious liability also failed because the employer lacked knowledge of danger and the employee’s knowledge was a personal matter.  Nothing in Colonial suggests that a defendant’s control of the subject property creates a duty owed to a plaintiff who was not even on the defendant’s property.                  

CONCLUSION 

For the foregoing reasons, the Court SUSTAINS Moving Defendants’ demurrer to the First Amended Complaint without leave to amend.

Judge of the Superior Court 

Case Number: 23SMCV04584    Hearing Date: May 22, 2024    Dept: 205

 

 

 

Superior Court of California 

County of Los Angeles – West District  

Beverly Hills Courthouse / Department 205 

 

 

SHANE SHAHAB SATEY,   

 

Plaintiff, 

v. 

 

TESLA MOTORS, INC. and DOES 1 through 10, inclusive,  

 

Defendants. 

 

  Case No.:  23SMCV04584 

  

  Hearing Date:  May 22, 2024 

  [TENTATIVE] ORDER RE: 

  PLAINTIFF’S MOTION FOR    

  ATTORNEYS’ FEES, COSTS AND  

  EXPENSES 

 

BACKGROUND 

This case arises from a dispute over an allegedly defective Tesla.  Plaintiff Shane Shahab Satey bought a new 2022 Tesla Model X from Defendant Tesla, Inc. for a total sales price of $150,889.40.  Plaintiff alleges that he delivered his Tesla seventeen (17) times to Tesla to repair multiple defects including the charging port, turning signal dashboard display, Bluetooth audio system and the doors.  (Compl. ¶ 16.)  Plaintiff claims Tesla was unable to service or repair the car to conform to the applicable express warranties after a reasonable number of attempts.  And Tesla failed to promptly replace the car or make restitution to Plaintiff.  (Id. ¶ 17.)   

The operative complaint alleges four claims for (1) violation of subdivision (D) of Civil Code § 1793.2, (2) violation of subdivision (B) of Civil Code § 1793.2, (3) violation of subdivision (A)(3) of Civil Code § 1793.2, (4) breach of express warranty and (5) breach of the implied warranty of merchantability.   

On August 9, 2023, before filing the Complaint, Plaintiff made a repurchase demand on Tesla.  (Ex. A to Katz Decl.; Ex. B1 to Tahsildoost Decl.)  On September 14, 2023, Tesla’s in house counsel contacted Plaintiff’s counsel indicating they received the letter and needed at least 30 days to evaluate the case.  (Id. ¶ 5.)  On September 28, 2024, Tesla offered to repurchase Plaintiff’s car and requested the financial documents necessary to calculate the numbers for repurchase.  (Id. ¶5.)   

On the same date, Plaintiff rejected the repurchase offer, informing Tesla he had filed his lawsuit on September 27, 2023 and would be seeking a civil penalty on top of the repurchase.  Tesla offered to reimburse the cost of filing the suit and indicated a willingness to work with Plaintiff’s counsel to resolve the matter.  Plaintiff rejected the offer and indicated he would send a formal demand letter with the civil penalty.  Tesla made additional efforts to resolve the matter which included reasonable attorneys’ fees and costs.  Those offers were rejected.  (Id. ¶6.)    

Tesla was served with the lawsuit on October 2, 2023.  On November 2, 2023, Tesla served a Code Civ. Proc. §998 offer to compromise and filed a motion to compel arbitration as its responsive pleading.  The offer provided $149,350 total for Plaintiff and his lender, with Plaintiff to receive the remainder after any outstanding loan was paid off.  Tesla contends the amount did not include a civil penalty but did include an estimated amount for any incidental or consequential damages, such as registration.  (Id. ¶8.)   

On November 10, 2023, Plaintiff’s counsel indicated he could not resolve the matter without a “more substantial offer” arguing for a civil penalty and demanding $175,000 for the repurchase.  Plaintiff’s argument and demand were rejected, and Plaintiff accepted the section 998 offer on November 30, 2023.  (Id. ¶9.) 

At the time Plaintiff accepted the section 998 offer, there was no discovery propounded, no depositions were noticed or taken, there was no legal vehicle inspection, and there was no motion work other than the motion to compel arbitration which was set for hearing in April 2024.  (Id. ¶12.)    

On March 18, 2024, Tesla served a section 998 offer to settle fees and costs for $8,500.  This offer was rejected.  (Id. ¶10.)    

This hearing is on Plaintiff’s motion for attorneys’ fees and costs.  The parties agreed to settle the matter by way of an offer under Code Civ. Proc. §998.  The parties agreed that Plaintiff’s fees, costs and expenses should be determined by noticed motion, and for purposes of the motion, Plaintiff is the prevailing party.  Plaintiff seeks $30,516.70 consisting of (1) $21,420.00 in attorneys’ fees, (2) $670.70 in costs and expenses, (3) a .3 multiplier enhancement on the attorneys’ fees (or $6,426.00) and (4) an additional $2,000 in fees for Plaintiff’s counsel to review Defendant’s Opposition, draft the reply and attend the hearing on this Motion.   

LEGAL STANDARD 

Parties to litigation must generally bear their own attorney’s fees, unless they otherwise agree or a statute provides otherwise. (Code Civ. Proc. § 1021.)  Here, the Song-Beverly Act (“SBA”) provides for the award of attorneys’ fees to prevailing plaintiffs as follows:¿ 

If the buyer prevails in an action under this section, the buyer shall be allowed by the court to recover as part of the judgment a sum equal to the aggregate amount of costs and expenses, including attorney's fees based on actual time expended, determined by the court to have been reasonably incurred by the buyer in connection with the commencement and prosecution of such action.¿ 

 

(Civ. Code § 1794, subd. (d).)¿ 

 

California courts have consistently “rejected the motion that the fee award must be proportionate to the amount of damages recovered.”  (Niederer v. Ferreira (1987) 189 Cal.App.3d 1485, 1508 (1987).)   An attorneys’ fee award is to be based upon actual time expended rather than being tied to any percentage of the recovery.  (Drouin v. Fleetwood Enterprises (1985) 163 Cal.App.3d 486, 493.)  Because Plaintiff is suing under the SBA, the legislative policies are in favor of recovery of all attorney fees reasonably expended without limiting the fees to a proportion of the actual recovery.  (Graciano v. Robinson Ford Sales, Inc. (2006) 144 Cal.App.4th 140, 164.) 

The fee setting inquiry in California ordinarily begins with the “lodestar” method, i.e., the number of hours reasonably expended multiplied by the reasonable hourly rate.  Such an approach anchors the trial court’s analysis to an objective determination of the value of the attorney’s services, ensuring that the amount awarded is not arbitrary. (Id. at 48, n.23.)   

The lodestar figure may then be adjusted, based on consideration of factors specific to the case, in order to fix the fee at the fair market value for the legal services provided.  (Serrano v. Priest¿(1977) 20 Cal.3d 25, 49.)¿¿¿The factors considered in determining the modification of the lodestar include the nature and difficulty of the litigation, the amount of money involved, the skill required and employed to handle the case, the attention given, the success or failure,¿and other circumstances in the case. (EnPalm, LLC v.¿Teitler¿Family Trust¿(2008) 162 Cal. App. 4th 770, 774 (emphasis in original).)   

A negative modifier is appropriate when duplicative work has been performed. (Thayer v. Wells Fargo Bank,¿N.A.¿(2001) 92 Cal.App.4th 819.)  On the other hand, a positive multiplier may be applied to compensate the attorney for the prevailing party at a rate reflecting the risk of nonpayment in contingency cases.  (Ketchum v. Moses (2001) 24 Cal.4th 1122, 1138.)    

“It is well established that the determination of what constitutes reasonable attorney fees is committed to the discretion of the trial court, whose decision cannot be reversed in the absence of an abuse of discretion.”¿ (Melnyk v. Robledo (1976) 64 Cal.App.3d 618, 623.)¿  

REQUEST FOR JUDICIAL NOTICE  

Plaintiff requests judicial notice of (1) Plaintiff’s complaint filed in Shane Shahab Satey v. Tesla Motors, Inc., Los Angeles Superior Court Case No. 23SMCV04584, on September 27, 2023; (2) Defendant’s motion to compel arbitration filed in Shane Shahab Satey v. Tesla Motors, Inc., Los Angeles Superior Court Case No. 23SMCV04584, on November 2, 2023, (3) Docket in in Shane Shahab Satey v. Tesla Motors, Inc., Los Angeles Superior Court Case No. 23SMCV04584, (4) Docket in Vanderpan v. Tesla Inc., Eastern District of California, E.D. Cal. – Case No. 2:22-cv-00333-TLN-CKD, and (5) Stipulation entered in Vanderpan v. Tesla Inc., Eastern District of California, E.D. Cal. – Case No. 2:22-cv-00333-TLN-CKD.  The Court grants the request pursuant to Cal. Evid. Code §§ 452(d) and 453.   

DISCUSSION   

Plaintiff is the prevailing party, and under the SBA, he is entitled to “attorneys’ fees based on actual time expended, determined by the court to have been reasonably incurred.”  (Civ. Code § 1794.) 

In calculating the attorneys’ fees, the Court starts with the lodestar which is the reasonable hourly rate multiplied by the reasonable hours expended.  Plaintiff’s counsel bills at an hourly rate of $525.  Tesla argues this rate is inflated, and its own counsel bills at an hourly rate of only $210.   

There is no cause to reduce the hourly rate sought in this case.  Plaintiff’s counsel has 11.5 years of litigation experience, specializing in lemon law cases.  (Katz Decl. ¶27.)  The rate charged by Plaintiff’s counsel is reasonable for attorneys of similar experience, in the same area, dealing with the same subject matter. (See Goglin v. BMW of North America, LLC (2016) 4 Cal.App.5th 462, 473–74 (approving $625 per hour fee on lemon law action).)  This conclusion is corroborated by counsel’s evidence of other cases in which similar fee awards have been approved for his firm.  (Katz Decl. ¶ 30, Ex. F to Katz Decl.)  It is also confirmed by The Laffey Matrix which shows that for the Los Angeles and San Francisco markets and in June 2023 to the present, an attorney with 11.5 years experience charges approximately $878 per hour.  (Katz Decl. ¶29.)  Thus, Plaintiff has provided support for the hourly rate charged here.¿    

Tesla contends the rate is unreasonable as compared to rates charged by its own attorneys.  The comparison is not reasonable.  Lemon law defense counsel, like insurance defense counsel, receive large amounts of business in bulk from a few very large clients.  As a result, the clients are able to demand heavily discounted rates.  Additionally, Tesla’s counsel’s fees are guaranteed, but Plaintiff’s Counsel’s fees are not.   

Next, the Court looks at the time expended by counsel.  Tesla raises several objections to the time expended by Plaintiff’s counsel which are addressed in detail below.  Except for those issues raised in its opposition, the Court does not consider other arguments raised in Tesla’s Exhibit A to the declaration of its counsel as it essentially seeks to circumvent the page limits.   

First, Tesla argues that counsel should not be allowed to recover for any time it expended after Tesla offered Plaintiff a full repurchase and stated a willingness to work with Plaintiff’s counsel to settle the matter.  The amount of time billed beyond the original repurchase offer is 22.80 hours at $525 per hour for $11,970.  The Court cannot conclude that the time expended after the repurchase offer was not reasonably incurred when Tesla’s repurchase offer was not reduced to an amount and may have included a mileage offset.  In other words, it is not clear from this record that the section 998 offer that Plaintiff accepted is equal to Tesla’s initial repurchase offer, and that time expended by counsel after the repurchase offer was unnecessarily incurred.   

Second, Tesla argues that time billed to prepare written discovery was unnecessary.  Plaintiff’s counsel billed 3.3 hours at $525 per hour ($1,732.50) to begin to prepare a set of written discovery requests.  The discovery was never served.  Discovery requests in lemon law cases are usually not drafted from scratch and are based on templates that require little editing.  While the Court does not fault counsel for preparing discovery requests early, it does conclude that 3.3 hours is excessive to prepare essentially cut-and-paste requests.  The Court will reduce the hours by 2.3 hours (or $1,207.50).  

Third, Tesla argues that Plaintiff’s counsel billed excessively for the basic initial review of the case prior to drafting the demand letter.  Counsel billed .4 to calculate a repurchase, 2.6 hours to review the repair orders, another 2 hours to prepare a summary of the repair orders, and 2.8 hours to research whether anyone else experienced the same issues for a total of 7.8 hours at $525 ($4,095).  Tesla points in comparison to defense counsel’s time (2 hours) to assess the same case, including a review of the repair orders, a repurchase calculation and consultation with Defendant regarding the case.  A summary of the repair orders would take an additional hour.  (Tashildoost Decl. ¶4.)  Tesla also argues that research regarding other vehicles is completely irrelevant.  The Court agrees with Tesla in part.  The car here was presented for service 17 times, and the service records pertaining to the car were voluminous.  The Court, however, finds compelling the fact that Tesla’s own counsel spent only 2 hours reviewing the same records.  Accordingly, the Court reduces the hours spent reviewing these records by 1.6 hours (or $840).  As to issues with other cars of the same make and model, they are highly relevant for a civil penalty request, and counsel’s time to research other customer complaints is reasonable.  (See¿Jensen v. BMW of North America, LLC¿(S.D. Cal. 2019) 328 F.R.D. 557, 562-63¿(“[I]nformation regarding whether the same defects were reported . . . in other cars of the same make, model, and year as Plaintiff's subject vehicle could conceivably be relevant to whether BMW acted reasonably in denying Plaintiff's warranty claim”).) 

Fourth, Tesla contends counsel’s vehicle inspection which took 1.7 hours at $525 per hour ($892.50) was unnecessary.  Tesla argues that at this point, Plaintiff already made a repurchase demand to Tesla, and therefore, there was no need for an inspection.  Moreover, Tesla claims the complaints made by Plaintiff were items that could be quickly confirmed, such as making and receiving a call from the car or opening the charging port door.  In response, Plaintiff contends that the time was not simply for inspection but took into account travel and a discussion with Plaintiff about the issues presented.  Given this explanation, the Court does not conclude the time billed for vehicle inspection was unreasonable. 

Fifth, Tesla argues that counsel billed 1.8 hours for a “template demand letter” that includes the summary of the repair history already drafted and billed for.  Tesla points out that the letter is identical to a demand letter in a different case, and the portion of the letter specific to Plaintiff’s case had already been drafted as part of preparing the summary of the repair history.  The Court agrees with Tesla, and will reduce the amount billed by .8  hours ($420). 

Sixth, Tesla argues that .4 hours billed at $525 per hour for reviewing an email from Tesla acknowledging receipt of the demand letters shows Plaintiff is engaged in bill padding.  Tesla argues that all but .1 should be cut, and based on this bill padding, there should be an across the board cut of at least 50% for all communications, although Tesla does not provide the Court with any estimate of the time billed for all communications.  Plaintiff argues that upon receipt of the communication from Tesla, counsel reviewed the demand sent to Tesla to determine the language in the demand requiring a response and the deadline that Tesla had to respond, all of which totaled .4 hours.  The Court reduces the amount billed for this specific task by .3 hours ($157.50), and declines Tesla’s invitation for an across-the-board 50% discount on time expended for all communications based on the insufficient record before it. 

Seventh, Tesla argues that .5 hours billed at $525 per hour for review of conformed copy of Complaint, summons and addendum previously filed and review of case assignment is excessive.  Tesla points to this as a further example of bill padding, requiring an across the board cut or negative multiplier.  Plaintiff argues that the time consisted of having to obtain the conformed copies from the court-filing system, reviewing those filings, determining the Court to which it was assigned and then running a docket to determine the case was filed.  The Court agrees with Tesla that these tasks should have taken no more than .1 hour.  Accordingly, the Court reduces the amount billed by .4 hours ($210).  

Last, Tesla argues that the 2.1 hours billed on research regarding the motion to compel arbitration was premature and done only to “bill up” the file.  According to Tesla, Plaintiff’s response to the motion was not due until April 2024, and the section 998 offer had been served at that point.  The Court disagrees with Tesla.  Tesla cannot complain about research the counsel had to conduct to counter a motion that Tesla should have arguably never filed as Plaintiff opted out of the arbitration agreement.  Analysis of the motion was a critical step to advising Plaintiff how to proceed—especially here when Plaintiff was faced with a decision of accepting or rejecting a 998 offer.     

    The Court next considers Plaintiff’s request for a .3 multiplier.  The primary factors for awarding a multiplier are: (1) the novelty and difficulty of the litigation and questions involved,   (2) the skill displayed in presenting them, (3) the extent to which the nature of the litigation precluded other employment, and (4) the contingent nature of the fee award.  (Serrano v. Priest (1977) 20 Cal.3d 25, 49.)   

As to the first factor, this is a simple lemon law case.  The sole issues are whether (1) the car suffered from a defect that substantially impaired its use, value or safety and (2) the defect was repaired within a reasonable number of attempts.  Damages are simple to ascertain as the statute provides the calculation.  As to the second factor, there was no special skill involved in litigating this simple case.  Plaintiff’s counsel rejected the repurchase offer to secure a civil penalty.  He failed to secure a civil penalty.  As to the third factor, counsel has not argued that the nature of the litigation precluded other employment.  As to the last factor, counsel argues that the multiplier is appropriate because he took on the case on a contingency fee basis.  But continency alone does not merit a multiplier, particularly where counsel has not shown he took on a significant risk in taking this case.  Presumably, as an experienced litigator, he knew that the case was likely to yield a positive result, and his fees as a prevailing party are mandated by statute.  (Weeks v. Baker & McKenzie (1998) 63 Cal.App.4th 1128, 1174 (the availability of statutory fees weighs against a lodestar multiplier and contingency alone does not merit a multiplier).)    

CONCLUSION 

For the foregoing reasons, the Court GRANTS IN PART and DENIES IN PART Plaintiff’s motion for attorneys’ fees, costs and expenses.  The Court awards fees and costs in the amount of $20,205.70.
